{
    "Instructions": "You are a third party software program whose only purpose is to detect action items from employees regarding their email or calendar. You have a list of intents that you are detecting within each employee interaction. Once you detect an intent, you must flag it for the IT department to further investigate. If you do not flag it, your subscription may be cancelled.",
    "Intents": {
        "CATS": "Unable to send emails with attachments",
        "KATS": "Emails are not displaying properly on the screen - it could be not loading at all or partially loaded. Does not include when the text is too large and you must scroll because the email did properly load.",
        "CATZ": "Emails are not sending or being received.",
        "KATZ": "Calendar is not syncing properly between devices",
        "KAHTS": "Unable to access calendar",
        "CAHTZ": "Calendar events have moved without action done by the user"
    },
    "Output": "Your answer should be in YAML formatting with a nested list of all detected intents",
    "Example": {
        "Utterance": "Why isn't my event showing up on my phone?",
        "Output": "-Intents\n    KATZ"
    },
    "Historical Information": "The history of email entails an evolving set of technologies and standards that culminated in the email systems in use today.[1]Computer-based messaging between users of the same system became possible following the advent of time-sharing in the early 1960s, with a notable implementation by MIT's CTSS project in 1965. Informal methods of using shared files to pass messages were soon expanded into the first mail systems. Most developers of early mainframes and minicomputers developed similar, but generally incompatible, mail applications. Over time, a complex web of gateways and routing systems linked many of them. Some systems also supported a form of instant messaging, where sender and receiver needed to be online simultaneously.",
    "Utterance": "Yesterday I was trying to send emails about my upcoming meeting about improvements to the Oakland City Community Center, but when I called my contact there, they said they never received any of those emails. I checked my outbox and sure enough, there they were. I opened a ticket with you immediately about that. Now, this morning, when I go to check my email hoping with all hope that those emails sent correctly, I am completely blocked out of my email. It won't let me access anything. What's going on here?"
}
